Subject: SD3 conditioner: pad shorter tokenizer vectors to chunk_count

`SD3CLIPEmbedder::get_learned_condition_common` derives a single
`chunk_count` from the longest of clip_l / clip_g / t5 token vectors,
then iterates that many chunks and slices each tokenizer's tokens with
`begin + (chunk_idx + 1) * chunk_len`.

Each tokenizer's `pad_tokens` pads independently and T5XXL routinely
tokenizes longer than CLIP (different vocabulary granularity), so a
moderately long prompt produces e.g. clip_l_tokens.size() == 77 (1
chunk) but t5_tokens.size() == 154 (2 chunks). chunk_count becomes 2
and the second iteration slices clip_l_tokens past .end() — undefined
behavior reading whatever is in heap memory beyond the vector's storage.

Symptoms:
  - CPU backend: GGML_ASSERT(i01 < ne01) failure in
    ggml_compute_forward_get_rows when the garbage int32 lands outside
    [0, vocab_size).
  - GPU backends (Metal / Vulkan / CUDA): no bounds check, so the
    garbage indices return arbitrary embedding rows. The "garbage"
    depends on heap state and varies per call, producing
    visually-similar-but-not-identical outputs across runs with the
    same seed and prompt — i.e. silent non-determinism on long prompts.

Fix: before the loop, extend each tokenizer's tokens vector out to
`chunk_count * chunk_len` by appending synthesized empty chunks via the
tokenizer's own `pad_tokens` (with empty input). Each appended chunk
has the model's normal empty-prompt structure (BOS + EOS + PAD for
CLIP, EOS + PAD for T5). The diffusion model sees real, in-distribution
embeddings for the missing-chunk positions instead of literal zero
vectors — same trick sd-webui's chunked prompt path uses.

Verified deterministic on: M3 Max + Metal + SD3.5 medium with
prompts up to 5 T5 chunks (~385 tokens) where CLIP is at 4 chunks.
Previously produced 4-of-5 different outputs on same-context runs
with seed=42 and a moderately long prompt; with the patch all 5
runs are byte-identical. Short prompts produce bit-identical output
to the pre-patch behavior (no regression).

Tracking: <upstream issue/PR url here once filed>

diff --git a/src/conditioner.hpp b/src/conditioner.hpp
--- a/src/conditioner.hpp
+++ b/src/conditioner.hpp
@@ -901,6 +901,32 @@ struct SD3CLIPEmbedder : public Conditioner {

         size_t chunk_count = std::max(std::max(clip_l_tokens.size(), clip_g_tokens.size()), t5_tokens.size()) / chunk_len;

+        // Each tokenizer's pad_tokens above runs independently, so a long
+        // prompt can give clip_l/clip_g 1 chunk while t5 gets 2+. The loop
+        // below slices each tokens vector with `(chunk_idx + 1) * chunk_len`,
+        // which would read past .end() on the shorter ones — undefined
+        // behavior (silent garbage embeddings on GPU, GGML_ASSERT crash on
+        // CPU). Pre-pad the shorter vectors out to chunk_count * chunk_len
+        // by appending synthesized empty chunks via each tokenizer's own
+        // pad_tokens (BOS+EOS+PAD layout — same structure the model saw
+        // for empty/short prompts during training). Gives in-distribution
+        // embeddings for the missing-chunk positions instead of zeros.
+        auto extend_to_chunk_count = [&](Tokenizer& tokenizer,
+                                         std::vector<int>& tokens,
+                                         std::vector<float>& weights) {
+            while (tokens.size() < chunk_count * chunk_len) {
+                std::vector<int> empty_tokens;
+                std::vector<float> empty_weights;
+                tokenizer.pad_tokens(empty_tokens, &empty_weights, nullptr,
+                                     chunk_len, chunk_len, false);
+                tokens.insert(tokens.end(), empty_tokens.begin(), empty_tokens.end());
+                weights.insert(weights.end(), empty_weights.begin(), empty_weights.end());
+            }
+        };
+        if (clip_l) extend_to_chunk_count(clip_l_tokenizer, clip_l_tokens, clip_l_weights);
+        if (clip_g) extend_to_chunk_count(clip_g_tokenizer, clip_g_tokens, clip_g_weights);
+        if (t5)     extend_to_chunk_count(t5_tokenizer,     t5_tokens,     t5_weights);
+
         for (int chunk_idx = 0; chunk_idx < chunk_count; chunk_idx++) {
             // clip_l
             sd::Tensor<float> chunk_hidden_states_l;
